        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "The main difference is when you pay taxes. Traditional IRAs are funded with pre-tax dollars (providing an upfront tax deduction), and withdrawals in retirement are taxed as ordinary income. Roth IRAs are funded with after-tax dollars, meaning no upfront deduction, but all qualified withdrawals in retirement—including growth and earnings—are completely tax-free."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What are the income limits for a Roth IRA?",
